AGI - Today's Supermedia data sounds a bit like a "back with feet on the ground" compared to what had been seen in the past few weeks". Also this time, in fact, the relations of force painted by the various polls are substantially unchanged compared to those we see now for months – that is, from the previous European elections.
<
<img src="https://public.flourish.studio/visualisation/21596450/thumbnail" width="100%" alt="chart visualization"
</div
&nbsp;
Starting with Fratelli d'Italia, than the “peak” of two weeks ago it loses slightly ground and returns, even a little, under the psychological threshold of 30%. In turn, the Democratic Party also yields something, more than half a point; but if for the Democrats this decline is compensated by the growth of other allied parties (or, however, they are also part of the opposition) such as the 5 Star Movement, More Europe or Italy Viva, in the district are all the parties to lose slightly ground.
&nbsp;
It is, with all evidence, of a sort of “rembalzo”, a return to normality after a period – lasted almost two months – actually positive for government parties. In this sense, it can be said that the date of the end of January with which we make comparisons today was the maximum point of a positive trend that concerned both the Brothers of Italy (who had grown over a point and a half compared to the Supermedia of 12 December) and the center-right, which in the same period had earned two exact points. It may seem little, but in a historical context like what we are living, in which for almost half of the legislature consensus remained extremely stable as it hadn't happened for many years, instead of significant movements.
<
<img src="https://public.flourish.studio/visualisation/11134413/thumbnail" width="100%" alt="chart visualization"
</div
At this point, it is then wondered what could trigger this trend reversal: it is rather immediate to attribute the increase in popularity of Giorgia Meloni and its government to the liberation of Cecilia Sala>, which took place in early January; a little less simple is to understand if – and to what extent – this most recent braking is linked to the controversies that have invested the executive in relation to the Almasri case and other potentially problematic events (e.g. the espionage of some journalists and activists through Israeli software Paragon).
&nbsp;
From the most recent data of the Youtrend survey for Sky Tg24, at least two potentially harmful issues emerge: the first is the position of the Minister of Tourism Daniela Santanchè>, who “saved” on the occasion of the parliamentary vote on the motion of distrust presented by the oppositions, but of which the majority of voters (also among those who vote center-right) hopes for resignation after referral to the case Visibilia.
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
Another “discounting” theme is the Almasri case >e in general <a href="https://www.agi.it/politica/news/2025-02-04/caso-almasri-informativa-alle-camere-plantedosi-nordio-29865381/"> to the management of the phenomenon of irregular immigration</a>: according to the data Youtrend Moreover, 52% of the respondents think it is wrong to send migrants to the centers built in Albania, an initiative that continues not to “decollate” because of legal and logistic obstacles still unresolved.
&nbsp;
To further complicate things, for the majority, a new fact could be involved, of which politics will certainly find itself discussing: the norm on assisted suicide adopted by the Tuscany Region, a measure that – at least for citizens of that region – fills a normative void denounced by a recent ruling of the Constitutional Court, but on which the Meloni Government does not seem in a condition to intervene by adopting a law valid throughout the national territory.
&nbsp;
Yet, on this theme, Italians seem to have quite clear ideas: more than 70% is favorable both to a law on assisted suicide and – similar but substantially different issue – to decriminalize the practice of euthanasia. What strikes, in data, is not only the entity of the majority of Italians in favor of these practices, but also the transversality of these positions: also among the voters of the center-right, in fact, the percentage of favors is much greater than that of the contrary, in this contradicting the official position of the parties (especially FDI and League) within which, to be true, there are positions dissident like that of the President of Veneto Luca Zaia. If the theme takes on national significance, it is likely that it will be transmuted into a potentially more harmful subject for majority parties than for opposition parties.
