AGI - "Ensure freedom of movement, provided for by the Constitution but today denied by the catastrophe of public transport not online and by an old law of more than thirty years. Introducing a revolutionary principle for Italy: It is the citizen who chooses the means of transport > which he prefers, not the State to limit its access. More competition, more benefits for consumers, more regular employment".
&nbsp;
These are some of the criteria that inspire the law of popular initiative that presented today to the House by the Association Article 16, born from the collaboration between the Italian Radicals and MuoverSi' (the federation that brings together the main NCC associations). The proposal introduces the concept of "transport to the public", >defined as the transport of persons from one place to another through any available mode, including digital platforms, and reiterates the separation with clear rules between taxi service and NCC service, > simplifying the granting of regional authorizations and aiming to ensure that the huge demand for public transport does not meet a safe and sufficient offer. To present the proposal are Mario Esposito, ordinary of constitutional law at the University of Salento and president of the Association Article 16; Andrea Giuricin, professor of Transport Economics at numerous international universities; Filippo Blengino, secretary of the Italian Radicals; Andrea Romano, president of MuoverSi', and many other representatives of the categories and associations involved. &nbsp;
&nbsp;
"Our proposal aims to unlock an old regulatory framework of more than thirty years: the law that regulates taxis and Ncc is 1992 when there were not even text messages.
Today everything has changed," explains Andrea Romano: "In citizens' habits, in mobility technology, in the right to have more shared mobility, less traffic and pollution, lower costs, more regular work for taxis and ncc. It is also for this reason that today in Italy to find a taxi is a desperate undertaking, with enormous damage to the right of everyone to free mobility and the same international credibility of Italy. But it is also a proposal for the Government and Parliament, to which we ask finally to open a legislative site to reform a key sector for our cities, for citizens, tourists and enterprises", concludes the President of MuoverSi Ncc.>
&nbsp;
&nbsp;
"We started months ago on this path from the urgency that hundreds of thousands of citizens feel to have a truly guaranteed service and that today is limited by a very limited category from the numerical point of view but very represented from the political point of view," explains the President of More Europe and the Italian Radicals, Matteo Hallissey: "This is an interesting proposal because &nbsp; not ideological, does not tell a distant utopia >, but tries to find a balance that puts citizens first, opening the sector and making it easier. A proposal that aims to collect many signatures, first online, then also on the territory. This proposal can be the draft, the starting canoe to reform the law in a total way". &nbsp;

